[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Science Council (WSC086)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Women in the wider STEM workforce[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]“Good practice benefits al
[normal]l, staff and students, men and women. However, bad practice adversely affects women’s careers more than men’s.”
[normal]“The age profile of the department, and the diversity of its staff, makes a difference. Young men and women with families have different expectations 
[normal]and needs from their older colleagues. Those younger staff members’ careers (and their science) cannot thrive unless the working culture of the department reflects the reality of dual career partnerships.”
[normal]Principle 1:
[normal]A robust organisational framework to deliver equality of opportunity and reward.
[normal]Principle 2: 
[normal]              
[normal]Appointment, promotion and selection processes and procedures that encourage men and women to apply for academic posts at all levels.
[normal]Principle 3
[normal]:
[normal]Departmental structures and systems that enable men and women to progress and continue in their careers.
[normal]Principle 4: 
[normal]              
[normal]Departmental organisation, structure, management arrangements and culture that are open, inclusive and transparent and encourage the 
[normal]participation of all staff.
[normal]Principle 5: 
[normal]              
[normal]Flexible approaches and provisions that encompass the working day, the working year and a working life and enable individuals, at all career and life stages, to maximise their contribution to mathematics, their d
[normal]epartment and institution.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]September 2013
